[[TITLE]] The Aster DSL Syntax
[[TAGS]] aster dsl language syntax
[[DESCRIPTION]] An in-depth explanation of the Aster DSL syntax.

The Aster DSL is a very consistent way. There is only one way to do most
semantic concepts, but each way may not be immediately intuitive for some. This
document goes over the important overall parts of the DSL's syntax, including
conditionals, loops, functions, and variables, among some more specialized
semantics.

[[HEADER]] Types
The DSL is statically typed. This means that all variables have one type known
at compile time, and can not be repurposed to store different types of data. The
DSL has several kinds of types, one "concrete" type (a type that directly means
a certain piece of data will be available on the device) and a handful of
"structural" types (a type used to aggregate variables into a more
understandable medium.

The one intrinsic "concrete" type is the bit. Bits are used to define more
complex data types in the form of arrays, where a type like a U32 is defined as
an alias to the statement [[I:bit@32]]. The "normal" instrinsic types (U8, S16,
etc.) one would expect a language to come with are defined in the standard
"basic" module provided with the Aster DSL installation, and are explained in a
later section of this manual page.

The instrinsic "structural" types are fairly easy to comprehend; the structure
("struct"), the bitmask ("bitmask"), the flagset ("flags"), and the union
("union"). A structure in the DSL is exactly as it is in C; an aggregation of
variables. However, the DSL provides functionality for giving structure
variables default arguments by assigning to them within the type declaration. A
union is identical to its usage in C, except it can be tagged, which is
discussed [[REF;dsl-advanced,later in this manual]].

"Bitmasks" and "Flagsets" are both variations of the C concept of an
"enumerator"; a symbolic value attached to a numeric constant for readability's
sake. In the case of a bitmask, these symbolic values can be bitwise ORed
together to allow multiple flags at once, while in the case of a flagset, each
flag is mutually exclusive. You can specify the underlying type of both a
bitmask and a flagset, which is discussed [[REF;dsl-advanced,later in this
manual]].

There is also the notion of an "alias" type. This like a [[I:typedef]] in C or a
[[I:using]] declaration in C++, it simply aliases one type to another. When
defining an alias, or in fact ANY type with a name, that name is expected to be
in all uppercase. This allows for easier visual distinction of type from
identifier when statically analyzing code.

When declaring a variable, the type is specified after the name, preceded by a
colon. This is similar in syntax to Jai.
